{
  "answer": "**The passage occurs in the *Kuñjarakarṇa Dharmakathana* (work slug: `unknown-kunjarakarna-dharmakathana-894f4a`), a Kawi (Old Javanese) Buddhist allegorical tale attributed to Mpu Dusun, in Chapter 1 (the entire work).**[^1]\n\nHere, the Buddha (Vairocana / Śākyamuni / Lord Sugata), seated in the monastery of Enlightenment, instructs the pupil Kuñjarakarṇa (an *asura* / *rākṣasa* ascetic) — later joined by Pūrṇavijaya — on the origins of the body as part of a sermon on karma, rebirth, and the five souls (*ātmā*, *parātmā*, *antarātmā*, *nirātmā*, *cetanātmā*), each linked to one of the five great elements (earth, water, fire, wind, ether).[^2]\n\nThe requested verse (Canto 17.8) reads:\n\n> It was from the passion of your father and mother that they were moved to unite.  \n> From the *liṅga* of your father you emerged, like molten tin, poured out.  \n> Indeed, Kāma is its name; Ratih is your name when you clung to your mother.  \n> There in the blossoming lotus of your mother's womb, you took on a definite form.[^3]\n\nThis imagery of sexual union and embryonic formation immediately precedes the exposition of the five-souls scheme.[^4]\n\n[^1]: *Kuñjarakarṇa Dharmakathana*, Chapter 1, [paragraph](/works/unknown-kunjarakarna-dharmakathana-894f4a/01/translation/#p-1082d7).\n\n[^2]: *Kuñjarakarṇa Dharmakathana*, Chapter 1, [paragraphs](/works/unknown-kunjarakarna-dharmakathana-894f4a/01/translation/#p-fd135e).\n\n[^3]: *Kuñjarakarṇa Dharmakathana*, Chapter 1, [paragraph](/works/unknown-kunjarakarna-dharmakathana-894f4a/01/translation/#p-1082d7).\n\n[^4]: *Kuñjarakarṇa Dharmakathana*, Chapter 1, [paragraphs](/works/unknown-kunjarakarna-dharmakathana-894f4a/01/translation/#p-4edd93).",
